21:25.360 --> 21:25.780
What gives?

21:26.400 --> 21:27.420
There's a good reason for that.

21:27.780 --> 21:30.260
Proctor told us that the book received only limited distribution.

21:31.460 --> 21:36.280
Heidelberg stopped publishing as best I can tell just about the time they brought out the book.

21:37.500 --> 21:42.140
There were big plans to do posters and everything to go with the book.

21:43.480 --> 21:46.040
Full posters of the cover, which the cover is gorgeous.

21:46.240 --> 21:47.660
It's one of those double take covers.

21:49.360 --> 21:53.360
And as it was, they sort of went out of business about that time.

21:54.240 --> 21:59.040
And far as I know, only a few thousand were distributed and they're still sitting in a warehouse somewhere.

22:00.160 --> 22:02.260
Making a scarce item.

22:04.460 --> 22:09.640
It's surprising that you go to conventions, large conventions in and out of state.

22:10.500 --> 22:14.380
And there will always be several people asking me how you get a copy of the book.

22:15.480 --> 22:17.720
It's rare because it was not distributed.

22:18.080 --> 22:20.140
And there's apparently tons of the books still around.

22:20.280 --> 22:21.520
You just can't get ahold of them.

22:22.740 --> 22:24.620
It's a nice item to have for a collector.

22:25.640 --> 22:28.260
Well, you can bet I'm going to be on the lookout for that book.

22:28.260 --> 22:31.720
In the meantime, we'll have more about Lone Star Universe on our next show.

22:39.100 --> 22:44.520
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association,

22:44.780 --> 22:47.660
produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

23:38.100 --> 23:42.020
Coming up next is the Science Fiction Radio Show, so stay with us.

23:58.260 --> 24:03.120
This is the Science Fiction Radio Show, a commentary on science fiction and fantasy.

24:05.940 --> 24:07.440
And here are your hosts.

24:11.500 --> 24:12.680
This is Daryl Lane.

24:12.860 --> 24:13.460
And Bill Vernon.

24:13.920 --> 24:17.960
Last time we talked about Lone Star Universe, the first regional science fiction anthology.

24:18.280 --> 24:23.360
Edited by George Procter and Stephen Utley, Lone Star Universe is a collection of short stories written by Texans.

24:23.360 --> 24:25.820
The anthology is a sought after collector's item.

24:25.940 --> 24:29.780
It's not readily available because it was poorly distributed when it was published in 1976.

24:30.380 --> 24:36.260
We talked with one of the editors, George Procter, and we asked him if the book might someday be reprinted, perhaps as a paperback.

24:37.120 --> 24:42.820
I don't think so because I think it is, you know, it's a limited item to Texana.

24:43.240 --> 24:48.660
I really think it has more value as Texana than it does to the science fiction field.

24:48.660 --> 24:52.220
As a whole, those science fiction collectors want it because it is a first.

24:56.320 --> 24:57.540
The stories are good.

24:57.960 --> 25:00.080
I think there's a wide variety of stories.

25:00.880 --> 25:08.060
Science fiction reviews that I saw of it, their complaint was that there was a wide variety of stories in there.

25:08.260 --> 25:10.160
It wasn't all nuts and bolts.

25:10.360 --> 25:13.520
It wasn't all new way, but there was everything.

25:13.520 --> 25:21.420
And that's the whole idea of the book was to show the diversity of the science fiction writers in this state.

25:23.520 --> 25:24.760
I think it did that well.

25:25.040 --> 25:27.660
I think it produced good stories by everybody that was in there.

25:28.580 --> 25:32.560
Procter told us that editing a second volume of Lone Star Universe is not out of the question.

25:35.280 --> 25:36.620
There may or may not be.

25:36.620 --> 25:45.900
It depends on, you know, I know of one person now who has his editor for a Texas publisher.

25:47.640 --> 25:58.340
And he has mentioned in passing that he'd like to get a hold of the first book since it never was really distributed.

25:58.480 --> 26:00.360
It's maybe buy them all out if possible.

26:01.560 --> 26:03.200
Well, they're not that'll ever happen.

26:03.960 --> 26:04.900
It's something else.

26:05.000 --> 26:05.780
But yeah, why not?

26:05.880 --> 26:06.360
It was fun.

26:07.660 --> 26:10.420
The people who got it seemed to enjoy it.

26:10.660 --> 26:15.920
And I still think if it would get some sort of distribution, it would be a money making book in Texas.

26:15.920 --> 26:34.660
Just the charisma of the state and the chauvinistic attitude of Texans, which is equivalent to New York, we're just larger.

26:37.140 --> 26:38.360
We buy Texana.

26:39.840 --> 26:41.800
Whether we read it or not, we buy it.

26:42.160 --> 26:44.740
And I think there's a market for it.

26:52.540 --> 27:00.740
So Proctor feels that Lone Star Universe might be more in demand as a collector's item for collectors of Texana than his reading material for science fiction readers.

27:01.140 --> 27:04.640
We ask him why Texas seems to be spawning so many new science fiction writers.

27:05.300 --> 27:06.560
They've always been around.

27:07.220 --> 27:10.220
They've never been noted as Texan before.

27:10.220 --> 27:22.780
And I think early 70s to mid 70s, we had a lot of fans who turned professional, started selling their stories.

27:23.240 --> 27:24.960
They were friends from all over the state.

27:25.740 --> 27:31.720
They suddenly became a very large group that we're selling and we're noticeable.

27:34.680 --> 27:44.180
That this group was here, had made it, gave a lot of other folks who wanted to write incentive to do it.

27:44.280 --> 27:55.000
And you've got suddenly a whole second wave of Texas writers coming out, meeting them here for the first time, that have just begun to sell their first stories or their first novel.

27:55.240 --> 27:58.720
But you've suddenly got a second wave of Texas science fiction writers, which is kind of nice.

27:59.780 --> 28:04.660
Texas writers have been rearing their heads recently and Lone Star Universe is an excellent anthology of their work.

28:05.260 --> 28:10.560
Other regions are producing a lot of science fiction these days, notably Oregon, Florida, upstate New York and New Orleans.

28:11.160 --> 28:15.860
But it was the Texans, with their bigger than life state and their pride, who produced the first regional anthology.

28:22.600 --> 28:31.800
This has been the Science Fiction Radio Show, production of the Permian Basin Science Fiction Association, produced in conjunction with Odessa College in Odessa, Texas.

